# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tauri-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:tauri-framework/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:tauri-framework/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:tauri-framework/sandbox-computer-security] In computer security, a **sandbox** is a security mechanism for separating running programs, usually in an effort to mitigate system failures and/or software vulnerabilities from spreading.
[src:tauri-framework/sandbox-computer-security] The sandbox metaphor derives from the concept of a child's sandbox—a play area where children can build, destroy, and experiment without causing any real-world damage.
[src:tauri-framework/sandbox-computer-security] It is often used to analyze untested or untrusted programs or code, possibly originating from unverified or untrusted third parties, suppliers, users or websites, without risking harm to the host machine or operating system.
[src:tauri-framework/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox typically provides a tightly controlled set of resources for guest programs to run in, such as storage and memory scratch space.
[src:tauri-framework/sandbox-computer-security] Network access, the ability to inspect the host system, or read from input devices are usually disallowed or heavily restricted.
[src:tauri-framework/sandbox-computer-security] In the sense of providing a highly controlled environment, sandboxing can be comparable to virtualization.
[src:tauri-framework/sandbox-computer-security] Sandboxing is frequently used to test unverified programs that may contain a virus or other malicious code without allowing the software to harm the host device.
[src:tauri-framework/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox is implemented by executing the software in a restricted operating system environment, thus controlling the resources (e.g. file descriptors, memory, file system space, etc.) that a process may use.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] A **single-page application** (**SPA**) is a web application or website that interacts with the user by dynamically rewriting the current web page with new data from the web server, instead of the default method of loading entire new pages.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] The goal is faster transitions that make the website feel more like a native app.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] In a SPA, a page refresh never occurs; instead, all necessary HTML, JavaScript, and CSS code is either retrieved by the browser with a single page load, or the appropriate resources are dynamically loaded and added to the page as necessary, usually in response to user actions.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] The origins of the term *single-page application* are unclear, though the concept was discussed at least as early as 2003 by technology evangelists from Netscape.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Earlier forms were called rich web applications.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] JavaScript can be used in a web browser to display the user interface (UI), run application logic, and communicate with a web server.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Mature free libraries are available that support the building of a SPA, reducing the amount of JavaScript code developers have to write.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] There are various techniques available that enable the browser to retain a single page even when the application requires server communication.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] HTML authors can leverage element IDs to show or hide different sections of the HTML document.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Then, using CSS, authors can use the `:target` pseudo-class selector to only show the section of the page which the browser navigated to.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Web browser JavaScript frameworks and libraries, such as Angular, Ember.js, ExtJS, Knockout.js, Meteor.js, React, Vue.js, and Svelte have adopted SPA principles.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Aside from ExtJS, all of these are free.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] The following frameworks utilize WebAssembly or can build single-page applications (SPAs) with WebAssembly as a core technology or support mechanism.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] These frameworks enable high-performance and interactive client-side development, extending the SPA paradigm across languages and ecosystems.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] As of 2006, the most prominent technique used was Ajax.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Ajax involves using asynchronous requests to a server for XML or JSON data, such as with JavaScript's XMLHttpRequest or more modern `fetch()` (since 2017), or the deprecated ActiveX Object.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] In contrast to the declarative approach of most SPA frameworks, with Ajax the website directly uses JavaScript or a JavaScript library such as jQuery to manipulate the DOM and edit HTML elements.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Ajax has further been popularized by libraries like jQuery, which provides a simpler syntax and normalizes Ajax behavior across different browsers which historically had varying behavior.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] WebSockets are a bidirectional real-time client-server communication technology that are part of the HTML specification.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] For real-time communication, their use is superior to Ajax in terms of performance and simplicity.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Server-sent events (SSEs) is a technique whereby servers can initiate data transmission to browser clients.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Once an initial connection has been established, an event stream remains open until closed by the client.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] SSEs are sent over traditional HTTP and have a variety of features that WebSockets lack by design such as automatic reconnection, event IDs, and the ability to send arbitrary events.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Although this method is outdated, asynchronous calls to the server may also be achieved using browser plug-in technologies such as Silverlight, Flash, or Java applets.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Requests to the server typically result in either raw data (e.g., XML or JSON), or new HTML being returned.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] In the case where HTML is returned by the server, JavaScript on the client updates a partial area of the DOM (Document Object Model).
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] When raw data is returned, JavaScript on the client translates it into HTML using XSL or a JSON template before updating the DOM.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] A SPA moves logic from the server to the client, with the role of the web server evolving into a pure data API or web service.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] This architectural shift has, in some circles, been coined "Thin Server Architecture" to highlight that complexity has been moved from the server to the client, with the argument that this ultimately reduces overall complexity of the system.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] The server keeps the necessary state in memory of the client state of the page.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] In this way, when any request hits the server (usually user actions), the server sends the appropriate HTML and/or JavaScript with the concrete changes to bring the client to the new desired state (usually adding/deleting/updating a part of the client DOM).
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] At the same time, the state in server is updated.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Most of the logic is executed on the server, and HTML is usually also rendered on the server.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] In some ways, the server simulates a web browser, receiving events and performing delta changes in server state which are automatically propagated to client.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] This is a variant of the stateful server approach.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] The client page sends data representing its current state to the server, usually through Ajax requests.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] This approach requires that more data be sent to the server and may require more computational resources per request to partially or fully reconstruct the client page state in the server.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] At the same time, this approach is more easily scalable because there is no per-client page data kept in the server and, therefore, Ajax requests can be dispatched to different server nodes with no need for session data sharing or server affinity.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Some SPAs may be executed from a local file using the file URI scheme.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] This gives users the ability to download the SPA from a server and run the file from a local storage device, without depending on server connectivity.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] If such a SPA wants to store and update data, it must use browser-based Web Storage.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] These applications benefit from advances available with HTML.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Because the SPA is an evolution away from the stateless page-redraw model that browsers were originally designed for, some new challenges have emerged.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Because of the lack of JavaScript execution on crawlers of some popular Web search engines, SEO (search engine optimization) has historically presented a problem for public facing websites wishing to adopt the SPA model.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Between 2009 and 2015, Google Webmaster Central proposed and then recommended an "AJAX crawling scheme" using an initial exclamation mark in fragment identifiers for stateful AJAX pages (`#!`).
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Special behavior must be implemented by the SPA site to allow extraction of relevant metadata by the search engine's crawler.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] For search engines that do not support this URL hash scheme, the hashed URLs of the SPA remain invisible.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] These "hash-bang" URIs have been considered problematic by a number of writers including Jeni Tennison at the W3C because they make pages inaccessible to those who do not have JavaScript activated in their browser.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] They also break HTTP referer headers as browsers are not allowed to send the fragment identifier in the Referer header.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] In 2015, Google deprecated their hash-bang AJAX crawling proposal.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Alternatively, applications may render the first page load on the server and subsequent page updates on the client.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] This is traditionally difficult, because the rendering code might need to be written in a different language or framework on the server and in the client.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Using logic-less templates, cross-compiling from one language to another, or using the same language on the server and the client may help to increase the amount of code that can be shared.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] In 2018, Google introduced dynamic rendering as another option for sites wishing to offer crawlers a non-JavaScript heavy version of a page for indexing purposes.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Dynamic rendering switches between a version of a page that is rendered client-side and a pre-rendered version for specific user agents.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] This approach involves your web server detecting crawlers (via the user agent) and routing them to a renderer, from which they are then served a simpler version of HTML content.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] As of 2024, Google no longer recommends dynamic rendering, suggesting "server-side rendering, static rendering, or hydration" instead.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Because SEO compatibility is not trivial in SPAs, SPAs are commonly not used in a context where search engine indexing is either a requirement, or desirable.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Use cases include applications that surface private data hidden behind an authentication system.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] In the cases where these applications are consumer products, often a classic "page redraw" model is used for the applications landing page and marketing site, which provides enough meta data for the application to appear as a hit in a search engine query.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Blogs, support forums, and other traditional page redraw artifacts often sit around the SPA that can seed search engines with relevant terms.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] As of 2021 and Google specifically, SEO compatibility for a plain SPA is straightforward and requires just a few simple conditions to be met.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] One way to increase the amount of code that can be shared between servers and clients is to use a logic-less template language like Mustache or Handlebars.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Such templates can be rendered from different host languages, such as Ruby on the server and JavaScript in the client.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] However, merely sharing templates typically requires duplication of business logic used to choose the correct templates and populate them with data.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Rendering from templates may have negative performance effects when only updating a small portion of the page—such as the value of a text input within a large template.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Replacing an entire template might also disturb a user's selection or cursor position, where updating only the changed value might not.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] To avoid these problems, applications can use UI data bindings or granular DOM manipulation to only update the appropriate parts of the page instead of re-rendering entire templates.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] With a SPA being, by definition, "a single page", the model breaks the browser's design for page history navigation using the "forward" or "back" buttons.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] This presents a usability impediment when a user presses the back button, expecting the previous screen state within the SPA, but instead, the application's single page unloads and the previous page in the browser's history is presented.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] The traditional solution for SPAs has been to change the browser URL's hash fragment identifier in accord with the current screen state.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] This can be achieved with JavaScript, and causes URL history events to be built up within the browser.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] As long as the SPA is capable of resurrecting the same screen state from information contained within the URL hash, the expected back-button behavior is retained.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] To further address this issue, the HTML specification has introduced pushState and replaceState providing programmatic access to the actual URL and browser history.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Analytics tools such as Google Analytics rely heavily upon entire new pages loading in the browser, initiated by a new page load.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] After the first page load, all subsequent page and content changes are handled internally by the application, which should simply call a function to update the analytics package.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Failing to call such a function, the browser never triggers a new page load, nothing gets added to the browser history, and the analytics package has no idea who is doing what on the site.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Similarly to the problems encountered with search engine crawlers, DAST tools may struggle with these JavaScript-rich applications.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Problems can include the lack of hypertext links, memory usage concerns and resources loaded by the SPA typically being made available by an Application Programming Interface or API.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Single-page applications are still subject to the same security risks as traditional web pages such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), but also a host of other unique vulnerabilities such as data exposure via API and client-side logic and client-side enforcement of server-side security.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] In order to effectively scan a single-page application, a DAST scanner must be able to navigate the client-side application in a reliable and repeatable manner to allow discovery of all areas of the application and interception of all requests that the application sends to remote servers (e.g.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] It is possible to add page load events to a SPA using the HTML History API; this will help integrate analytics.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] The difficulty comes in managing this and ensuring that everything is being tracked accurately – this involves checking for missing reports and double entries.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Some frameworks provide free analytics integrations addressing most of the major analytics providers.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Developers can integrate them into the application and make sure that everything is working correctly, but there is no need to do everything from scratch.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] There are some ways of speeding up the initial load of a SPA, such as selective prerendering of the SPA landing/index page, caching and various code splitting techniques including lazy-loading modules when needed.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] But it's not possible to get away from the fact that it needs to download the framework, at least some of the application code; and will hit an API for data if the page is dynamic.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] This is a "pay me now, or pay me later" trade-off scenario.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] The question of performance and wait-times remains a decision that the developer must make.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] A SPA is fully loaded in the initial page load and then page regions are replaced or updated with new page fragments loaded from the server on demand.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] To avoid excessive downloading of unused features, a SPA will often progressively download more features as they become required, either small fragments of the page, or complete screen modules.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] In this way an analogy exists between "states" in a SPA and "pages" in a traditional website.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] Because "state navigation" in the same page is analogous to page navigation, in theory, any page-based web site could be converted to single-page replacing in the same page only the changed parts.
[src:tauri-framework/single-page-application] The SPA approach on the web is similar to the single-document interface (SDI) presentation technique popular in native desktop applications.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit started as a fork of the KHTML and KJS libraries from KDE, and has since been further developed by KDE contributors, Apple, Google, Nokia, Bitstream, BlackBerry, Sony, Igalia, and others.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit supports macOS, Windows, Linux, and various other Unix-like operating systems.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] On April 3, 2013, Google announced that it had forked WebCore, a component of WebKit, to be used in future versions of Google Chrome under the name Blink.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Since version 15 in May 2013, Opera web browser has dropped its own Presto layout engine in favor of WebKit as implemented by Google in the Chromium project.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Its JavaScript engine, JavaScriptCore, also powers the Bun server-side JS runtime, as opposed to V8 used by Node.js, Deno, and Blink.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit's C++ application programming interface (API) provides a set of classes to display Web content in windows, and implements browser features such as following links when clicked by the user, managing a back-forward list, and managing a history of pages recently visited.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit is open source and available under the BSD 2-Clause license with the exception of the WebCore and JavaScriptCore components, which are available under the GNU Lesser General Public License.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] As of March 7, 2013, WebKit is a trademark of Apple, registered with the United States Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The code that would become WebKit began in 1998 as the *KDE HTML* (KHTML) layout engine and *KDE JavaScript* (KJS) engine.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The WebKit project was started within Apple by Lisa Melton on June 25, 2001, as a fork of KHTML and KJS.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Melton explained in an e-mail to KDE developers that KHTML and KJS allowed easier development than other available technologies by virtue of being small (fewer than 140,000 lines of code), cleanly designed, and standards-compliant.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] KHTML and KJS were ported to macOS with the help of an adapter library and renamed to WebCore and JavaScriptCore.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] JavaScriptCore was announced in an e-mail to a KDE mailing list in June 2002, alongside the first release of Apple's changes.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The exchange of code between WebCore and KHTML became increasingly difficult as the code bases diverged, because both projects used different coding approaches and had different approaches to code sharing.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] At one point KHTML developers said they were unlikely to accept Apple's changes and claimed the relationship between the two groups was a "bitter failure".
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] They claimed Apple submitted their changes in large patches containing multiple changes with inadequate documentation, often in relation to future additions to the codebase.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Thus, these patches were difficult for the KDE developers to integrate back into KHTML.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Also, Apple had demanded that developers sign non-disclosure agreements before looking at Apple's source code, and even then, they were unable to access Apple's bug database.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] During the publicized "divorce" period, KDE developer Kurt Pfeifle (*pipitas*) posted an article claiming KHTML developers had managed to backport many (but not all) Safari improvements from WebCore to KHTML, and they always appreciated the improvements coming from Apple and still do so.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The article also noted that Apple had begun contacting KHTML developers to discuss improving the relationship and future cooperation.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] In fact, the KDE project was able to incorporate some of these changes to improve KHTML's rendering speed and add features, including compliance with the Acid2 rendering test.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Following the appearance of a story of the fork in the news, Apple released the source code of the WebKit fork in a public revision-control repository.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The WebKit team also reversed many Apple-specific changes in the original WebKit codebase and implemented platform-specific abstraction layers, making it significantly easier to commit the core rendering code to other platforms.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] In July 2007, *Ars Technica* reported that the KDE team would move from KHTML to WebKit.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Instead, after several years of integration, KDE Development Platform version 4.5.0 was released in August 2010 with support for both WebKit and KHTML, and development of KHTML continued until 2016 before it was officially discontinued in 2023.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] On June 7, 2005, Safari developer Dave Hyatt announced on his weblog that Apple was open-sourcing WebKit (formerly, only WebCore and JavaScriptCore were open source) and opening up access to WebKit's revision control tree and the issue tracker.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] In mid-December 2005, support for Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) was merged into the standard build.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit's JavaScriptCore and WebCore components are available under the GNU Lesser General Public License, while the rest of WebKit is available under the BSD 2-Clause license.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Beginning in early 2007, the development team began to implement Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) extensions, including animation, transitions and both 2D and 3D transforms; such extensions were released as working drafts to the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) in 2009 for standardization.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] In November 2007, the project announced that it had added support for media features of the HTML5 draft specification, allowing embedded video to be natively rendered and script-controlled in WebKit.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] On June 2, 2008, the WebKit project announced that they had rewritten JavaScriptCore as "SquirrelFish", a bytecode interpreter.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The project evolved into SquirrelFish Extreme (abbreviated SFX), announced on September 18, 2008, which compiles JavaScript into native machine code, eliminating the need for a bytecode interpreter and thus speeding up JavaScript execution.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Initially, the only supported processor architecture for SFX was the x86, but at the end of January 2009, SFX was enabled for macOS on x86-64 as it passes all tests on that platform.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] On April 8, 2010, a project named WebKit2 was announced to redesign WebKit.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Its goal was to abstract the components that provide page layout and rendering cleanly from their surrounding interface or application shell, creating a situation where "web content (JavaScript, HTML, layout, etc) lives in a separate process from the application UI".
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] This abstraction was intended to make reuse in WebKit2 simpler than in WebKit.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit2 had "an incompatible API change from the original WebKit", which motivated its name change.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The WebKit2 targets were set to Linux, macOS, Windows, GTK, and MeeGo-Harmattan.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Safari for macOS switched to the new API with version 5.1.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Safari for iOS switched to WebKit2 with iOS 8.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The original WebKit API has been renamed WebKitLegacy API.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit2 API has been renamed just plain WebKit API.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit is used as the rendering engine within Safari and was used by Google's Chrome web browser on Windows, macOS, and Android (before version 4.4 KitKat).
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Chrome used only WebCore, and included its own JavaScript engine named V8 and a multiprocess system.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Chrome for iOS continues to use WebKit because Apple requires that web browsers on that platform must do so.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Other applications on macOS and iOS make use of WebKit, such as Apple's e-mail client Mail, App Store, and the 2008 version of Microsoft's Entourage personal information manager, both of which make use of WebKit to render HTML content.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] New web browsers have been built around WebKit such as the S60 browser on Symbian mobile phones, BlackBerry Browser (ver 6.0+), Midori, Chrome browser, the Android Web browsers before version 4.4 KitKat, and the browser used in PlayStation 3 system software from version 4.10.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] KDE's Rekonq web browser and Plasma Workspaces also use it as the native web rendering engine.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit has been adopted as the rendering engine in OmniWeb, iCab, Web (formerly named Epiphany), and Sleipnir, replacing their original rendering engines.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] GNOME's Web supported both Gecko and WebKit for some time.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Still, the team decided that Gecko's release cycle and future development plans would make it too cumbersome to continue supporting it. webOS uses WebKit as the basis of its application runtime.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit is used to render HTML and run JavaScript in the Adobe Integrated Runtime application platform.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] In Adobe Creative Suite CS5, WebKit is used to render some parts of the user interface.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] By the first half of 2010, an analyst estimated that 350 million mobile handsets had shipped with a WebKit-based browser.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] By mid-April 2015, WebKit browser market share was 50.3%.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The week after Hyatt announced WebKit's open sourcing, Nokia announced that it had ported WebKit to Symbian and was developing a WebKit-based browser for mobile phones running S60.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Named Web Browser for S60, it was used on Nokia, Samsung, LG, and other Symbian S60 mobile phones.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Apple has also ported WebKit to iOS for the iPhone, iPod Touch, and iPad, where it is used to render content in the device's web browser and e-mail software.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The Android mobile phone platform used WebKit (and later versions its Blink fork) as the basis of its web browser and the Palm Pre, announced January 2009, has an interface based on WebKit.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The Amazon Kindle 3 includes an experimental WebKit based browser.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] In June 2007, Apple announced that WebKit had been ported to Microsoft Windows as part of Safari.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Although the company silently discontinued Safari for Windows, WebKit's ports to Microsoft's operating system are still actively maintained.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The Windows port uses Apple's proprietary libraries to function and is used for iCloud and iTunes for Windows, whereas the "WinCairo" port is a fully open-source and redistributable port.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit has also been ported to several toolkits that support multiple platforms, such as the GTK toolkit for Linux, under the name *WebKitGTK* which is used by Eolie, GNOME Web, Adobe Integrated Runtime, Enlightenment Foundation Libraries (EFL), and the Clutter toolkit.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Qt Software included a WebKit port in the Qt 4.4 release as a module called QtWebKit (since superseded by Qt WebEngine, which uses Blink instead).
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The Iris Browser on Qt also used WebKit.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The Enlightenment Foundation Libraries (EFL) port – EWebKit – was developed (by Samsung and ProFusion) focusing the embedded and mobile systems, for use as stand alone browser, widgets-gadgets, rich text viewer and composer.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The Clutter port is developed by Collabora and sponsored by Robert Bosch GmbH.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] There was also a project synchronized with WebKit (sponsored by Pleyo) called *Origyn Web Browser*, which provided a meta-port to an abstract platform to make porting to embedded or lightweight systems quicker and easier.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] This port is used for embedded devices such as set-top boxes and PMP and it has been ported into AmigaOS, AROS, and MorphOS.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] MorphOS version 1.7 is the first version of Origyn Web Browser (OWB) supporting HTML5 media tags.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] On April 3, 2013, Google announced that it would produce a fork of WebKit's WebCore component, to be named Blink.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Chrome's developers decided to fork WebCore to allow greater freedom in implementing its features in the browser without causing conflicts upstream, and to simplify its codebase by removing code for WebCore components unused by Chrome.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] In relation to Opera Software's announcement earlier in the year that it would switch to WebKit by means of the Chromium codebase, it was confirmed that the Opera web browser would also switch to Blink.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Following the announcement, WebKit developers began discussions on removing Chrome-specific code from the engine to streamline its codebase.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit no longer has any Chrome specific code (e.g., buildsystem, V8 JavaScript engine hooks, platform code, etc.).
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebCore is a layout, rendering, and Document Object Model (DOM) library for HTML and Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG), developed by the WebKit project.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Its full source code is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL).
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] WebKit passes the Acid2 and Acid3 tests, with pixel-perfect rendering and no timing or smoothness issues on reference hardware.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] JavaScriptCore is a framework that provides a JavaScript engine for WebKit implementations, and provides this type of scripting in other contexts within macOS.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] JavaScriptCore is originally derived from KDE's JavaScript library KJS (which is part of the KDE project) and the PCRE regular expression library.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] Since forking from KJS and PCRE, JavaScriptCore has added many new features and greatly improved performance.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] On June 2, 2008, the WebKit project announced they rewrote JavaScriptCore as "SquirrelFish", a register-based bytecode interpreter replacing the original AST-walking interpreter.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] The project later evolved into SquirrelFish Extreme (abbreviated SFX, marketed as Nitro), announced on September 18, 2008, further speeding up JavaScript execution by introducing Just-in-time compilation.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] An optimizing just-in-time (JIT) compiler named *FTL* was announced on May 13, 2014.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] It uses LLVM to generate optimized machine code.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] "FTL" stands for "Fourth-Tier-LLVM", and unofficially for faster-than-light, alluding to its speed.
[src:tauri-framework/webkit] As of February 15, 2016, the backend of FTL JIT is replaced by "Bare Bones Backend" (or B3 for short).
[src:tauri-framework/webview] A **WebView** is a web browser that is embedded within an app.
[src:tauri-framework/webview] Thus, a WebView is a large-scale software component that enables the use of web content within apps.
[src:tauri-framework/webview] In some cases, the entire functionality of the app is implemented this way.
[src:tauri-framework/webview] Other examples are Microsoft's legacy WebView, based on its deprecated EdgeHTML and MSHTML engines, and the WebView component in JavaFX.
